<task type="auto" tdd="true">
  <name>Task 1: GENERAL nested def/rep-level computer + list-of-struct write support in MzPeakParquet</name>
  <files>ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/MzPeak/MzPeakParquet.cs, ThermoRawFileParser/ThermoRawFileParserTest/MzPeakParquetTests.cs</files>
  <behavior>
    - A general computer (`NestedLevels`) takes any leaf DataField in a schema of nested StructFields and ListFields plus a per-row description of presence/values, and returns the `(defined, defLevels, repLevels)` triple. It computes max-def-levels FROM THE SCHEMA SHAPE — NOT a flat 1. For the existing fixtures it reproduces the measured levels: top-struct leaf max-def 1 ([1,0,1]); nested struct-in-struct leaf max-def 2 ([2,0,2]); list-of-struct leaf path `…/list/item/…` def {5 present-elem, 4 leaf-null-in-present-elem, 2 empty-list, 0 null-list} with rep {0 first-elem/new-row, 1 subsequent-elem}.
    - On the ACTUAL Phase-3 shapes the computer is correct: (a) a `precursor.isolation_window` nested-struct present vs null; (b) a `precursor.activation.parameters` list with null-list, empty-list, and list-with-N-items rows; (c) a `scan.scan_windows` list with one window per row; (d) a top-level struct (precursor) that is NULL on the right-padded tail rows. Each case round-trips: writing N rows then reading back via pyarrow yields the exact per-row list lengths, the exact present/null pattern per leaf, and representative leaf values.
    - Rep-levels and def-levels produced by the computer are accepted by Parquet.Net 5.0.1 WriteColumnAsync AND by a pyarrow reader (no schema/level mismatch) for every shape above.
  </behavior>
  <action>
    Extend MzPeakParquet with a GENERAL per-leaf level computer (e.g. `NestedLevels`) for arbitrary nested shapes built from StructField/ListField/DataField. Given the schema path to a leaf and a per-row presence/value description, it must correctly express ALL of: top-level struct present vs null; nested struct-in-struct (e.g. `isolation_window`) present vs null; a list that is null vs empty vs has N items; and a null leaf inside a present element. Derive each leaf's max-def-level by walking its ancestor chain (each nullable struct level and each list level contributes), and emit rep-level 0 for the first element of a new list (new row) and 1 for subsequent elements within the same list. Do NOT hard-code def-level 1: the existing tests require mz_range leaves at max-def 2 and list leaves at 5/4/2. Keep `WriteAsync` keying columns by DataField identity, unchanged. Build list fields as `new ListField(name, BuildParamField("item"))` for PARAM lists and a `ListField` over a `StructField` for scan_windows — the list element MUST be named `item` (the conventional Arrow/Parquet.Net list-item name; the leaf path is `…/list/item/…`). Reuse `BuildParamField` for the PARAM element; do NOT introduce a second PARAM struct definition. Compact code, explicit usings, no comments referencing process/phases.
    In MzPeakParquetTests, add a test that exercises the computer on the actual Phase-3 shapes in ONE schema: a `precursor` top-level struct containing `isolation_window` (nested struct with target/offset leaves) and `activation.parameters` (PARAM list), plus a `scan` struct with `scan_windows` (list-of-struct). Write a known ragged set: a row with isolation_window present + activation.parameters of 2 items, a row with isolation_window present + EMPTY activation list, a row with a NULL activation list, a scan_windows row with one window, and null-padded TAIL rows where the whole `precursor` struct is null. Then shell out to `python3 -c` using pyarrow to read it back and print per-row list lengths, the per-leaf present/null pattern, and a representative leaf value; assert the printed values match the written shape exactly (including empty-list != null-list and the null tail). Mirror any existing pyarrow-invocation pattern in the test file; otherwise invoke `python3` via Process and parse stdout. Skip-with-warning (`Assert.Ignore`) if `python3`/pyarrow is unavailable so the suite stays green without pyarrow.
  </action>
  <verify>
    <automated>cd /Users/kohlbach/Claude/mzPeak4TRFR && DOTNET_ROOT_X64=$HOME/.dotnet-x64 ~/.dotnet-x64/dotnet test ThermoRawFileParser/ThermoRawFileParser.sln --filter "MzPeakParquetTests" 2>&1 | tail -15</automated>
  </verify>
  <done>The general level computer reproduces the existing measured levels (top-struct max-def 1, nested struct max-def 2, list leaves 5/4/2) AND round-trips the actual Phase-3 shapes (isolation_window present/null, activation.parameters null-list/empty-list/N-items, scan_windows, null-padded precursor tail) under pyarrow — exact per-row list lengths, present/null patterns, and leaf values. Empty-list and null-list are distinguished. No other MzPeakParquetTests regress. The rep/def-level unknown (RESEARCH Open Q1 / Pitfall 3) is retired before any metadata facet is built on it — this computer underpins Tasks 2-3.</done>
</task>

<task type="auto" tdd="true">
  <name>Task 2: rich `spectrum` + required `scan` facet as co-resident null-padded tables</name>
  <files>ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs, ThermoRawFileParser/ThermoRawFileParserTest/MzPeakWriterTests.cs</files>
  <behavior>
    - spectra_metadata.parquet has a `scan` top-level struct with `source_index:uint64` non-null for all N emitted ordinals; `scan.source_index == scan.scan_index == row ordinal`.
    - `spectrum` carries: index(u64), id(string nativeID `controllerType=0 controllerNumber=1 scan=N`), MS_1000511_ms_level(u8), time(f64), MS_1000465_scan_polarity(int8 +1/-1), MS_1000525_spectrum_representation (CURIE MS:1000127 centroid / MS:1000128 profile from actual array continuity), MS_1000559_spectrum_type (CURIE MS:1000579 MS1 / MS:1000580 MSn), lowest/highest observed mz (unit MS:1000040), number_of_data_points(u64), number_of_peaks(u64, NULLABLE), base_peak_mz (unit MS:1000040), base_peak_intensity (unit MS:1000131), total_ion_current (unit MS:1000131), and a `parameters` PARAM list.
    - COUNT DISCIPLINE (representation-specific, dual model): `number_of_data_points` = the spectrum's `spectra_data` point count for that ordinal; `number_of_peaks` = the spectrum's `spectra_peaks` count when peaks were written for that ordinal, else NULL (null def-level, NOT 0).
    - `scan` carries: source_index, scan_index, MS_1000016_scan_start_time_unit_UO_0000031 (float32, raw Thermo minutes, NO conversion), MS_1000512_filter_string, MS_1000927_ion_injection_time_unit_UO_0000028 (float32), instrument_configuration_ref (u32 = 0-based analyzer-config index), and a `scan_windows` list (lower MS_1000501 / upper MS_1000500, unit MS:1000040) from scan LowMass/HighMass.
    - polarity is an int8 SIGN (+1/-1), NOT a CURIE; representation/type ARE CURIE strings.
  </behavior>
  <action>
    Widen the existing Phase-2 per-scan loop to capture, per emitted ordinal, the rich spectrum + scan fields using the Thermo calls in the reuse table (RESEARCH Decision 2; do NOT re-decode). Map each column with `MzPeakParquet.CvColumn(accession,label,unit)` per RESEARCH Decision 3 (note: scan_start_time/ion_injection_time/scan window limits/base-peak-intensity/TIC are float32; observed-mz/base-peak-mz are double). Set `id` to the Thermo nativeID via the base `ConstructSpectrumTitle`/equivalent (`controllerType=0 controllerNumber=1 scan=N`) — keep it deterministic. ms_level from `(int)scanFilter.MSOrder`; polarity from `scanFilter.Polarity` (Positive->(sbyte)1, Negative->(sbyte)-1); representation from the actual array continuity already determined by the Phase-2 centroid/profile routing (centroid->MS:1000127, profile->MS:1000128); spectrum_type from ms_level (1->MS:1000579 else MS:1000580).
    COUNT DISCIPLINE (RESEARCH Decision 2/3, dual model): `number_of_data_points` = the per-ordinal `spectra_data` point count (always present). `number_of_peaks` = the per-ordinal `spectra_peaks` count ONLY when peaks were written for that ordinal; when no peaks were written for that ordinal emit NULL (def-level 0) — never 0. Both counts come from the Phase-2 per-ordinal accumulators that already track which ordinals received a data array and which received a peaks array. TIC/base-peak/observed-mz from ScanStatistics / the emitted arrays.
    Build the instrument-configuration index map: collect the DISTINCT `scanFilter.MassAnalyzer` values in first-seen order across the run; each distinct analyzer is one config (0-based). `scan.instrument_configuration_ref` = the index of that scan's analyzer in this list (RESEARCH Decision 5; reference order 0=FTMS,1=ITMS). Persist this map for Task 4's instrument_configuration_list.
    Rewrite `BuildMetadataFacet` to assemble ONE ParquetSchema with the `spectrum` and `scan` top-level StructFields (both full-length: def-level 1 for all N rows, via the Task-1 computer). Use the Task-1 list-of-struct path for `spectrum.parameters` and `scan.scan_windows` (list element named `item`). Keep the leaf-lookup-by-path `Leaf(schema,...)` pattern. Keep footer KV `spectrum_count` and `spectrum_array_index` consistent with Phase 2.
    Compact code, explicit usings, BOM-free, no process/phase comments.
    Add NUnit locks in MzPeakWriterTests: convert small.RAW (existing TestRawFile), open the metadata parquet, and assert — scan facet present with source_index==scan_index==ordinal for all rows; spectrum CV column NAMES exactly match the ground-truth schema (drive the assertion off the schema field names); the scan_windows list element path is `scan/scan_windows/list/item/…` (pyarrow schema-name assertion) and parameters path is `…/parameters/list/item/…`; polarity leaf is int8 with value in {-1,1}; representation/type are CURIE strings of the expected form; number_of_data_points matches the spectra_data per-ordinal row count; on small.RAW assert a profile+centroid scan has number_of_peaks populated AND a scan with no peaks written has number_of_peaks NULL (not 0).
  </action>
